The tops of post-eruptive arcades can be seen emerging from beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 171 starting at about 2025-01-07T23:48Z. There is some uncertainty in the exact location of this eruption since this is not directly on the disk, but it is very likely associated with Active Region 13939 which is estimated to have been located at roughly S17W99 at the peak time of the flare [2025-01-07T23:05Z].

This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2025-01-17T15:53Z. The source of this CME are back to back M1.8 and M1.1 flares and an associated eruption from AR 3964 (N07W33). This flare can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with a Northern region of dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 suggesting a possible Northern deflection.

note: Faint CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-01-17T22:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the N/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is an M1.7 flare and subsequent eruption involving brightening, dimming, and a post-eruptive arcade from AR 3964 (N06W34) and the surrounding area beginning at approximately 2025-01-18T00:48Z as seen in SDO/AIA 131, 193, 304, and in a few frames of 211 (currently at a reduced cadence). This CME overlaps with the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-01-18T02:00Z.

note: This CME is visible to the N/NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and to the N/NE in STEREO A COR2 following the front of the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-01-18T01:36Z. There are two potential sources for this CME. The first source of this CME could be associated with the same M1.7 flare from AR 3964 (N06W34) as the 18/01:36Z CME, however there is a simultaneous small filament eruption from an area to the SE of the main flaring AR location. This filament eruption (~S15W12) is the second potential source and is located above the large Earth-facing coronal hole which may have contributed to significant deflection of the CME.

CME partially overlaps with CME: 2025-01-18T15:48Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, not STEREO COR2A due to a data gap. This CME front is quite faint and diffuse. The source may be a dimming eruption from AR 3964 (N04W44) starting around 2025-01-18T13:10Z with a second pulse of field line movement and brightening around T13:51Z in SDO AIA 171, with some dimming in SDO AIA 193. This unclean eruption may explain the diffuse nature of the CME. CME follows and partially overlaps with CME: 2025-01-18T15:12Z.

The source for this CME does not appear to be observed in SDO AIA, GOES SUVI, or STEREO A EUVI, but its direction in both coronagraphs and measurement heavily direct towards a far-sided source around W120-W130. There is a brief filament eruption over the SW limb starting around 2025-01-21T04:38Z in STEREO A EUVI 304, but that is quite early for this signature and that filament is believed to be responsible for CME: 2025-01-21T05:00Z instead.

Despite the complexity of the two overlapping CMEs in LASCO imagery in the southeast, this CME being seen to the west in STEREO A suggests far-sidedness.

note: Bright CME and faint shock to the SE in STEREO COR2A, not yet observed in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 due to a downlink gap except for a very few late SOHO C3 frames. Starting around 2025-01-21T09:42Z, a wide area of the disk East and South of AR 13967 brightens up in SDO AIA 304/GOES SUVI 304 with observed filament ejecta fanning out to the SE. Field line movement and extensive dimming, with an EUV wave, over this area also observed in SDO AIA 171/193/211. Partially overlaps with far-sided CME: 2025-01-21T09:12Z.

note: Narrow CME seen due south in SOHO LASCO which appears to be associated with a minor eruption from near Active Region 13967 (S20E25) and broad dimming signature seen best in SDO/GOES 193/195, respectively, following a much larger eruption occurring 2025-01-21T10:20Z. Source is a large eruption from the southwest quadrant of the disk, from the large Active Region 13961 which was centered at S10W28 at the time of the eruption. Dimming starting at 2025-01-22T10:43Z extends from S10-S50 and from W10-W40 as seen in SDO AIA 193. Opening field lines and ejecta can be seen in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 304, respectively. It is possible that two small filaments lifted off in this eruption, however, there is filamentary material visible/reformed after the eruption. An M1.3 flare from AR 13961 with peak time 2025-01-22T11:08Z is associated with this event. This CME visually overlaps with the far-sided CME:2025-01-22T08:36Z.

Filamentary material and post eruptive brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-01-25T00:45Z. Post-eruptive arcades become visible in SDO AIA 171/193/131 around 2025-01-26T02:27Z.

Opening field lines are seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284 starting at 2025-01-28T08:05Z, and the absence of post-eruptive arcades and/or dimming on the Earth-facing disk further suggests this eruption is beyond the SW limb.

note: CME first seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-01-28T20:12Z. CME is also seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C3 and is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is possibly a small eruption from near the E limb (~S07).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the SW with the source the minor opening of field lines on/likely behind the SW limb starting at 2025-01-29T18:33Z as seen in AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SW by STEREO A COR2, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in SOHO LASCO C2 due to a data gap from 30/04:00Z to 30/07:36Z. The source of this CME is field line movement seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284, suggesting a far sided source location.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen to the SW beginning at 2025-01-30T09:12Z, as well as by STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This event is overtaken by CME: 2025-01-30T11:12Z in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is rising field line loops seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-01-30T11:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is field line opening seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195, indicating a far sided source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Flux rope CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. CME not captured by STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which started at 2025-01-30T15:09Z. The source is a filament eruption seen beginning at approx. 2025-01-30T13:49Z in SDO AIA 304, spanning approx. S05E05 to S40E40. Dimming and post eruptive arcades are also visible in SDO AIA 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint partial-halo CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, which remains visible into the C3 field of view. Overlaps with CME:2025-01-30T16:12Z, which is much more well-defined in coronagraph imagery. This CME is not captured by STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which started at 2025-01-30T15:09Z. The source of this CME is a distinct set of opening field lines and post-eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94/171/193 around 2025-01-30T14:25Z located at approx. S15E10, as part of the same filament eruption which sourced CME:2025-01-30T16:12Z, which was seen beginning at approx. 2025-01-30T13:49Z in SDO AIA 304, spanning approx. S05E05 to S40E40.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Loop CME seen to the West in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This CME is not captured by STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which started at 2025-01-30T15:09Z. The source of thus event is field line opening seen along/from just beyond the Western limb starting at 2025-01-30T17:57Z in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the W/NW. The source is an M6.7 flare from AR13978 (N14E43), based on SDO/AIA 131 imagery, peaking at 2025-01-31T14:06Z. Associated filament ejecta is visible in SDO/AIA 304 starting around 2025-01-31T13:51Z. Moving/opening field lines and EUV wave are also visible along the NW limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-01-31T14:00Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow eruption seen to the west in SOHO/STEREO A associated with a minor eruption near the vicinity of Active Region 13979 near S10W55, exhibiting some westward deflection seen in GOES 284/304 and SDO 193/171/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor, faint loop appearing to the west-northwest in SOHO LASCO imagery following behind the outflow of CME: 2025-02-01T14:24Z to the west. Likely associated with a far-sided eruption as evidenced by moving field lines seen off the northwest limb best in GOES 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Asymmetric loop CME seen to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 during a STEREO A data gap. Likely associated with far-sided activity as evidenced by a breaking/disappearing magnetic field line/loop seen far off the southwestern limb in GOES 284 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible as a far-sided halo directed towards the south/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, with a fast opening of field lines visible over the southwest limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284 imagery starting around 2025-02-02T05:38Z. Eruptive material is also visible over/beyond the southwest limb starting around 2025-02-02T06:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 imagery. It is possible this event is associated with former Active Region 13961, which was located approximately around longitude 170-175 degrees at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This event is visible to the west/northwest in STEREO A COR2, but is it not observed in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no corresponding signatures on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event. There is an eruption visible beyond the southwest limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery starting around 2025-02-02T10:15Z and again around 13:15Z, but both of these eruptions appear too far south to be associated with this event.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely associated with an eruption and M5.1 flare from Active Region 13977 (N20E03) starting around 2025-02-02T14:00Z which deflects to the northeast as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 and GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-02T18:36Z. This event is too faint to be reliably tracked in SOHO LASCO C3 and is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 02/15:23Z. The source of this event is field line movement seen near AR 3977 (N19E04) beginning at approx. 2025-02-02T18:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Far sided halo CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-02T21:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is far sided field line opening seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. This CME overlaps with CME: 2025-02-02T22:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Far sided halo CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-02T21:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is far sided field line opening seen along the SW limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. This CME overlaps with CME: 2025-02-02T21:24Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen to the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-02T23:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 02/15:23Z. The source of this CME is an M4.1 flare from Active Region 3981 (N05E25) beginning at 02/23:04Z. This flare can be seen in SDO AIA 131 along with field line opening seen exhibiting a Southern deflection seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and in STEREO A COR2 following a data gap from 2025-02-02T15:23Z to 2025-02-03T02:53Z. The source may be related to a faint opening of field lines observed over the southeast limb starting around 2025-02-03T00:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a filament eruption spanning S45W40 to S35W80 which begins to lift-off around 2025-02-03T11:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the southwest limb at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery as well. The eruption exhibits a southern deflection, which was confirmed in the measured parameters.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Fast asymmetrical and relatively narrow CME to the SE, covered by a data gap in STEREO A. It source is a narrow filament eruption seen at 2025-02-04T00:02Z in SUVI 284/304 and AIA 304 on SE limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Streamer-like loop CME seen due north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and northeast in STEREO A COR2. The source is a large rising loop seen over the N/NE limb in GOES SUVI 284 seen starting at 2025-02-03T20:38Z. Corresponding field line movement on the Earth-facing disk centered over a large cluster of Active Regions in the northern hemisphere (ARs 13976, 13977, 13978, 13981, and 13982) and minor post-eruptive brightening seen at N30E20 at 2025-02-04T08:38Z in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop CME seen to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 and south in STEREO A COR2. Becomes diffuse after a few frames of SOHO LASCO C3. The source is field line movement seen beyond the southern limb starting at 2025-02-04T01:48Z in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SSE is SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-02-04T08:24Z. Also seen to the SSE in SOHO LASCO C3 and to the SSW in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely some very faint moving field lines visible beyond the southern limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about an hour prior to the CME start time. A far-sided source fits well with measured parameters.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3, not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is unclear but may be associated with moving/opening field lines visible along the NE limb in SDO/AIA 171 starting around 2025-02-04T09:00Z and continuing through 2025-02-04T13:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Minor, narrow CME seen to the south-southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, likely associated with a far-sided eruption at extreme southern latitudes as evidenced by flickering field lines in SDO AIA 171 seen off the southeast limb around 2025-02-04T21:00Z. STEREO A imagery is not available to support triangulation.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-02-05T02:12Z. Also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3 and to the S in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is a filament eruption from the SW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk easily seen across SDO EUV wavelengths. The filament is best seen beginning to lift off at approximately 2025-02-05T00:10Z in SDO AIA 304. The footpoints of the filament were located at approximately S35W27 and S30W65.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint puff-like CME seen to the east-northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 coronagraph imagery and not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery except for one frame. Associated with a spray/prominence eruption taking place off the eastern limb seen in GOES SUVI 284 with strong northern/northeastern deflection. The CME is characterized by a very slow moving bulk and fainter shock-like feature which accelerates outward ahead of the bulk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Minor, narrow CME seen to the southeast in SOHO C2 and presumably to the south in STEREO A COR2A, seemingly associated with a far-sided minor filament eruption seen around 18:00Z to the southeast in GOES SUVI 304 and SDO AIA 304. Triangulation suggests the CME originates from near a longitude of -145 degrees.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Relatively slow, loop CME seen to the east-northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, brightly in running difference imagery and faintly in white light imagery. There are few if any sources on the Earth-facing disk or off of the east/northeast limb to suggest that this CME is associated with eruptive activity on the Earth-facing limb, therefore, it likely originates from the far-side of the solar disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Narrow CME seen to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery, brightly in running difference imagery and faintly in white light imagery. Likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity as evidenced by moving magnetic field lines seen off the southeast limb best in GOES SUVI 284, but as well in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME seen to the SE fully in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and to the S/SW potentially as a partial halo in STEREO COR2A after 2025-02-06T05:09Z, with the CME front already at the edge of its FOV when its beacon data downlink resumes. Due to this data gap timing in STEREO COR2A, the CME is observed in white light imagery but unresolvable in running difference imagery. Observed as a rapid snapping open and dimming of field lines over the SE limb centered ~S28, best observed in SDO AIA 171/193 around 2025-02-06T02:31Z and GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-02-06T02:34Z. Also observed in SDO AIA 304/GOES SUVI 304 as some filament ejecta. The far-sided nature of this CME is also corroborated via fitting in swpc_cat and the lack of an on-disk signature accompanying the field line movement.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright filament eruption to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source is a filament eruption occurring on/beyond the NW limb as viewed from SDO AIA and GOES SUVI, first seen on the NW limb as viewed from STEREO A EUVI 304 at 2025-02-06T10:15Z, confirmed to be separate from the M7.6 flare (AR 13981) that occurred on the earth-facing disk at this same time. Also observed starting around 2025-02-06T10:36Z in SDO AIA 304/GOES SUVI 304, launching more explosively around 2025-02-06T11:32Z. Also seen well as the filament ejecta and field line movement in SDO AIA 171/193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, outflow like CME first seen in the South by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-06T15:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2025-02-06T15:23Z to 2025-02-07T02:53Z. The source of this event is faint field line movement seen along the South limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright lightbulb CME first seen in the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-07T03:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen along the SE limb in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-07T08:24Z. This CME appears to fade before exiting the FOV in SOHO LASCO C2. The source of this event is an M3.2 flare from AR 3981 (N06W27) peaking at 07/07:21Z seen in SDO AIA 131. Post eruptive arcades are visible in SDO AIA 94 and 131, along with a region of dimming seen in SDO AIA 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Faint CEM first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-07T11:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is very minor field line movement seen along the NE limb in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor CME seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 during a STEREO A data gap; the CME is likely associated with a far-sided eruption occurring behind the southeastern limb, as evidenced best by moving field lines seen off the southeast limb in GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. Candidate source is a small amount of brightening seen from AR 13981, followed by dimming and field line movement (centered at N00W45) just to the southwest of AR 13981, which starts at 2025-02-08T00:39Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. Source is an M2.0 flare and associated eruption from AR 13981 (N07W41). Opening field lines and dimming seen starting at 2025-02-08T09:09Z, best seen in SDO AIA 193. The eruption is also seen from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not visible in SDO AIA imagery, but an eruption can be seen just on or beyond the southwest limb in STEREO A EUV 304 imagery starting at 2025-02-08T12:45Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint CME to the northwest only seen in several SOHO LASCO C2 images and largely obscured by the pylon in C3 imagery. The CME is fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A imagery. No clear coronal signatures have been found for this CME, although some very minor activity is going on in the northwest, possibly from AR 13978 (N14W77).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME to the east, with pointed and fuzzy nose. The CME is fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A coronagraph imagery. Its source is a filament eruption off the east limb (N10E90) which starts around  2025-02-10T00:01Z, as seen in SDO AIA 171/304 and GOES SUVI 284/304 imagery. The filament could be further behind the limb, so its longitude could differ from -90 degrees.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: A super faint jet to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in STEREO A COR2 (and in difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2) and only seen in 2-3 early timestamps in SOHO LASCO C3 because of extreme faintness of this event. No source was found on the Earth-facing disk, so it is likely a farsided event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the east/southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to a faint eruption visible slightly beyond the southeast limb in SDO AIA 304 imagery starting around 2025-02-10T11:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

The source is likely related to an eruption on/near the eastern limb starting around 2025-02-10T17:50Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A faint opening of field lines is visible over the northeast limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 at this time as well.

Source is an M1.6 flare and associated eruption from AR 13981 (N05W87). Opening field lines and brightening are seen starting around 2025-02-11T05:27Z, best seen in SDO AIA 131, but also seen in SDO AIA 171/193/304. The eruption is also seen from the point of view of STEREO A EUV 195/304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Bright CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption and associated C5.8 flare located at N15E75. Opening field lines, a rising loop, and ejecta are seen starting at 2025-02-11T06:12Z in SDO AIA 193/171/304/131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source is best observed in SDO AIA 304 as a filament eruption on the eastern limb around S10E90, beginning around 2025-02-11T17:48Z and erupting more explosively around 2025-02-11T18:04Z. Also observed as field line opening in SDO AIA 171/193, and a C7.2 flare peaking at 2025-02-11T18:25Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-12T02:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is not entirely clear. However, a region of brightening is visible in SDO AIA 94 located at approx. N10E70 beginning at approx. 12/02:24Z. A 2-coronagraph measurement indicates that the CME likely resulted from activity in this area, however, due to the timing, this brightening may be post-eruptive arcades from an eruption that is not as visible opposed to the actual source of the CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the south-southwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap starting at 2025-02-12T10:38Z. The source appears to be a filament eruption visible along the south-southwestern limb in SDO/AIA 304, GOES SUVI 304, and STEREO A EUVI 304 starting around 2025-02-12T06:00Z. Moving/opening field lines are also visible in SDO/AIA 171, GOES SUVI 284, and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-12T13:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2025-02-12T10:38Z to 2025-02-13T03:23Z. The source of this CME is a minor eruption seen located at approx. N15E47 in SDO AIA 193, 211 and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at approx. 2025-02-12T18:00Z. This event fades before exiting the FOV in SOHO LASCO C3, and is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2025-02-12T10:38Z to 2025-02-13T03:23Z. The source of this event is a very gradual filament eruption seen centered at approx. S50W40 in SDO AIA 304, with movement beginning at approx. 12/13:00Z. Field line opening is seen much later in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284 beginning at approx. 12/16:49Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 20254-02-12T21:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This event is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 2025-02-12T10:38Z to 2025-02-13T03:23Z. This filament eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery, showing post-eruptive arcades and brightening stretching from N35W60 to N15W90, near AR 3989 (~N20W85) [30 degrees have been added to all STEREO A EUVI longitudes to translate to Earth-facing disk coordinates].

note: CME first seen in the West by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-26T06:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not clearly visible in STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is a filament eruption centered at approx. S10W25 exhibiting a strong Westward deflection. This filament is visible in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUVI 304, along with dimming and post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94, 193 and STEREO A EUVI 195. A large North-South configured coronal hole is visible approximately 10 degrees to the East of the eruptive source. This coronal hole may cause deflection or acceleration of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very faint CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-26T09:36Z. This event fades before exiting the FOV in C2, and is therefore not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 or STEREO A COR2. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Bright CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and after a data gap in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is a filament eruption seen near S30W70 in SDO/AIA, STEREO A EUVI and GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-02-26T14:00Z. There is strong southern deflection of the eruption, likely due to the large coronal holes to the north and east of the source location. Field line opening is also visible in SDO/AIA 171, 193, and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the W/SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in a few frames of STEREO A COR2 imagery before a data gap beginning around 2025-02-26T19:00Z. The exact start time of this CME is unclear due to the overlap with the CME first seen in SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-02-26T15:00Z. The possible source of this CME is a filament eruption beginning around 2025-02-26T11:15Z in STEREO A EUVI, GOES SUVI, and SDO/AIA 304 imagery near ~S15W90+. A slow rising loop is visible in GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery along the W/SW limb starting around 2025-02-26T12:00Z which may have been fully released from the lower/middle corona when the filament eruption associated with the overlapping CME to the SW occurred.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in limited imagery in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The CME exhibits an initial faint, diffuse front with a brighter portion (more clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery) that appears to be the bulk of the CME. The source appears to be a possible filament eruption stretching along the eastern side of the large N-S oriented coronal hole located near central meridian. Brightening is visible in SDO/AIA and GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-02-26T14:16Z. Associated dimming and post-eruptive arcades are visible in SDO/AIA 195 and GOES SUVI 284. Deflection is likely for this CME due to the large coronal holes to the west of the source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west/southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. This event is not observable in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. Faint field line movement is visible over the southwest limb at this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C3 imagery. It is also visible in SOHO LASCO C2 following a data gap ending at 2025-02-27T07:48Z. The source is likely related to an eruption from Active Region 13996 (S16W89) starting around 2025-02-27T05:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131 and 304 imagery. Faint field line movement is visible over the southwest limb around this time in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C3, SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very faint and wide loop CME first seen to the NW in STEREO A COR2 and seen after a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2. The leading edge is nearly fully obstructed by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. note: CME visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Brightening and dimming are seen from the region, and opening field lines are best seen in SDO AIA 171/193/284.

note: CME visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-02-27T15:23Z. Moving/opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171/193 and dimming is visible in SDO AIA 193.

note: CME first seen the the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-28T08:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is field line opening seen just beyond the SW limb in SDO AIA 193. This may be related to activity from AR 3996 (S16W100) which rotated off of the Earth facing disk on 2025-02-27.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-02-28T15:23Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. The source of this event is a jet-like eruption from Active Region 4006 (N18W02), exhibiting a very strong Northeastern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304.

note: Bright, partial halo to halo CME visible in the W/NW of SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is a far-sided filament eruption visible along the NW limb of STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 starting around 2025-02-28T16:45Z. Post eruptive arcades are also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 starting around 2025-02-28T17:35Z. Moving/opening field lines and an EUV wave is visible in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-02-28T17:00Z. The source is suspected to be from AR 13993 (~N15W125) based on available STEREO A EUVI data. Note that there was a simultaneous, much less significant, eruption centered at (~W01W60) at the time of the far-sided eruption associated with this CME.

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-02-28T16:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a C5.2 flare and jet-like eruption from Active Region 4006 (N18W02), exhibiting a very strong Northeastern deflection in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. This CME partially overlaps and is obscured by CME: 2025-02-28T17:12Z in later frames.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the north in SOHO LASCO C2 with fainter loops following shortly behind. Associated with a point source eruption from near AR 4006 (N18W10) starting at 2025-03-01T09:18Z with very strong deflection north out of the ecliptic as evidenced by dark filamentary material jetting north in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery with a very bright core mostly on the right side of the CME. The source is a large L-shaped filament eruption stretching from ~S35W10 to ~S15E40 centered around ~S35E20 starting around 2025-03-01T17:00Z. Brightening is visible in SDO/AIA, GOES SUVI, and STEREO A EUVI 304. Dimming, moving/opening field lines, and post-eruptive arcades are best visible in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO/AIA 193.

note: This CME is visible in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery to the S/SE in the outflow of the previous CME starting at 2025-03-01T18:24Z. It is not visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to a data gap beginning at 2025-03-01T21:38Z. The source of this CME is a partially occulted C9.5 flare from a region just beyond the SE limb near S26E90+ as seen in SDO/AIA and GOES SUVI 131 imagery. A well defined loop with filament ejecta in the middle is seen lifting from the source region with clear moving/opening field lines and EUV wave to the south starting around 2025-03-01T23:00Z. There appears to be strong deflection to the south with this event as evident by the moving/opening field lines in GOES SUVI 284 imagery.

note: Narrow faint jet to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in running difference imagery. Its source is likely a C2.4 class flare (and a super minor ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 304) from AR 4011 (S18E58) starting at 2025-03-02T03:37Z.

note: Faintest of the 3 consecutive narrow jets from AR 4011 this morning. Its source is likely the C1.2 flare from AR 4011 (S18E57) starting at 2025-03-02T05:46Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint narrow CME to the southeast in both coronagraphs, best seen in running difference imagery. note: Bright heart-shaped CME to the northwest in both coronagraphs. Most likely this is a backsided CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint loop only seen in COR2A running difference imagery and overlapping with the earlier more significant 2025-03-02T10:24Z CME; this event is not clearly seen in SOHO; the actual start might be earlier. No source has been found.

The source may be related to a large southwest filament eruption spanning S55W15 to S40W60 seen in SDO AIA 304 imagery starting around 2025-03-03T11:28Z. An associated dimming region is visible in SDO AIA 193 around this time centered near ~S60W20. Due to the data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery at this time, it is difficult to confirm with a triangulated measurement if this event is related to the filament eruption.

Associated moving/opening field lines and possible EUV wave visible to the south and south west towards the south pole as seen in SDO/AIA 193 indicating southern deflection, likely due to the coronal hole located N/NE of the source location. Associated brightening and dimming are also visible in SDO/AIA 131, 304, and 193 in the area of the source with additional dimming visible further south closer to the south pole.

The potential source for this CME is a filament eruption near S42W95 with associated moving/opening field lines visible along the SW limb in SDO/AIA 304 and 171 starting around 2025-03-04T03:51Z. There appears to be southward deflection possibly due to coronal holes in the vicinity of the source location. The coronal holes and the eruptions deflection are more clearly seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 imagery.

instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

S20-S25 and E110-E90) starting at about 2025-03-05T03:34Z in SDO AIA 171 imagery. Post-eruptive brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304, including some from nearby AR 4012 (S13W06) starting at 2025-03-07T21:04Z. instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is faint but visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. It is too faint to observe in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided and may be related to faint field-line movement visible over the southwest limb starting around 2025-03-10T10:25Z as seen in SDO AIA 171 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faint but visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery before the leading edge becomes too diffuse to observe. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk at the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and relatively narrow CME to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 and SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The leading edge appears slightly brighter in STEREO A COR2 than in SOHO LASCO. The source is opening field lines seen starting at 2025-03-11T03:35Z located on or just beyond the W limb as seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 (W120-130 from SDO AIA perspective) and spanning approximately N00 to S10 in latitude, although the eruption likely extends to farther beyond the limb. Field line movement and the disappearance of a small loop of material can be seen from the same location in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery between the 2025-03-11T03:45Z and 2025-03-11T04:45Z frames.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Super narrow jet (with the 2 degree half-width or so), seen only in SOHO LASCO C2 and faintly in a few early timestamps of C3. Not discernible in STEREO A COR2, likely because of its faintness. Likely associated with the M1.1 flare from AR 14024 (N5W47).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, relatively fast CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and more directed towards the north in STEREO Ahead COR2 imagery composed of a fainter, faster shock. No sources on the Earth-facing disk in EUV imagery seem to be associated with this event, so the CME is likely associated with far-sided eruptive activity.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME seen to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 during a COR2A data gap. Appears to be associated with a minor eruption from Active Region 14024 (N07W57) and C9.6-class flare as evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 294 starting around 2025-03-11T21:28Z as well as brightening visible in SDO AIA 131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow, relatively fast CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap; it appears similar in appearance to the CME: 2025-03-11T18:24Z which was determined to likely be far-sided. Few, if any sources on the Earth-facing disk suggest that this CME occurs with eruptive activity on the Earth-facing disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bulbous jet-like CME to northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the north in STEREO, similar to the 2025-03-11T23:24Z CME. No clear source was found on disk but there are some movements of field lines behind the limb in the NE after 05Z in AIA 193. The CME is likely farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A super faint jet to the northwest, seen mostly in SOHO LASCO C2 and in a few early timestamps of C3 and too faint to be seen in STEREO A COR2. There is no flare that can be associated with it but there is some brightening in AR 14024 after 2025-03-12T06Z seen in SDO AIA 193 and it is possibly associated with activity in this Active Region.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Super faint and narrow jet only seen in SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery and in a few early C3 images and not seen in STEREO A COR2. No source has been found for this jet.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 white light imagery starting at 2025-03-12T20:04Z. Also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not seen in STEREO A COR2. This jet may have been visible in running difference imagery shortly before it was visible in white light imagery and has a half-width of less than ten degrees. There is not a good source candidate on the Earth-facing disk; however, there are some possible post eruptive arcades on or just beyond the NE limb (approximately N35-N40) best seen in SDO AIA 171 beginning around 2025-03-12T21:15Z that could be related to this jet.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the SSE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source may be field line movement in SDO AIA 171 observed over the SSW limb beginning around 2025-03-12T23:18Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO COR2A for a few frames before it fades, never reaching LASCO C3 imagery. First seen more clearly in SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery at 2025-03-13T03:48Z. The source for this CME is likely field line movement in SDO AIA 171 on or just inside the SE limb starting around 2025-03-13T02:53Z, from the northern side of AR 14028.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SW in STEREO COR2A only, as SOHO LASCO C2/C3 is in a data gap from 2025-03-13T07:30Z -> 2025-03-13T22:10Z. No source for this CME is observed in SDO AIA or STEREO A EUVI imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 composed of a bright narrow bulk and a fainter shock extending to the north and west relative to the bulk. The source is a minor eruption from near Active Region 4020 (N20E13) with northern deflection as seen in SDO AIA 193, 171, 304 as early as 2025-03-13T16:49Z; darkening in SDO AIA 193, brightening in SDO AIA 304 and the appearance of a breaking loop in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and east-northeast in STEREO A COR2A composed of a bright narrow bulk extending to the northeast and second more minor outflow seen more to the north. The source may be associated with a minor eruption seen near the eastern limb around E80 as early as 2025-03-14T02:00Z; mostly in GOES SUVI 284 imagery, or the eruption may be far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-14T15:25Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 14/15:53Z. The source of this event is a minor eruption from AR 4022 (N08E11) beginning at approx. 14/14:28Z. Dimming seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211 suggest a strong Eastern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: An extremely narrow faint jet seen mostly in running difference imagery in SOHO and STEREO A to the northeast. No clear source has been found in the EUV imagery at the time but there is a super minor ejecta in SDO AIA 304 at 01:40Z on the NE limb which may be related.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is additional wide and subtle field line movement seen on and very likely extending beyond the SW limb, best seen in STEREO A EUVI 193, and likely a direct consequence of or sympathetic eruption to a filament eruption seen starting at to lift off the southwest limb at 2025-03-15T04:09Z as seen in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:36Z, whose source is the filament eruption on the southwest limb.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note:
One of two overlapping loop CMEs visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2. The source is a filament eruption on the southwest limb, spanning from about S25W85 to S10W120 with southward deflection seen as it erupts in SDO AIA and STEREO-A EUV imagery. This CME heavily overlaps with CME: 2025-03-15T05:24Z, whose source is nearly simultaneous and in close proximity. 

Filamentary material is seen starting to lift off at 2025-03-15T04:09Z in SDO AIA 304, 193, and 171. Post-eruptive arcades can be seen in SDO AIA 193 and 171 starting at 2025-03-15T06:28Z and lasting for multiple hours. Bright material can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 as well. This eruption is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 193 imagery, which has frames available after a data gap ending at 2025-03-15T03:45Z and reveals liftoff of material starting with the next frame with timestamp 2025-03-15T04:15Z. With STEREO A currently at a HEEQ longitude of 31, this vantage point reveals that there was a filament eruption and a separate but sympathetic rising loop directly next to the filament, which altogether extended from approximately S25W80 to S10W121 (coordinates listed as would be seen by SDO. STEREO A is currently at a HEEQ longitude of +31 degrees).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow faint jet seen to the northeast in a couple of early timestamps in SOHO LASCO C2. Not seen in STEREO A COR2. A possible source is a narrow bright ejecta on/behind the east limb in AIA 304 around 2025-03-15T18:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Complex-shaped, somewhat pointy-nosed and possibly partial halo CME to the southwest, seen the brightest in STEREO A COR2. Its source is behind the SW limb (both in SDO and in STEREO A) and likely associated with Active Region 4012 (now at approximately W125) which was fairly complex when it was on the Earth-facing disk; its coronal signatures are fast-opening field lines behind the SW limb in both EUV imagers starting at 2025-03-16T00:32Z, as seen in SDO AIA 193/171, EUVI A 195 and SUVI 285. Much later (after 05Z) some high post-eruptive arcades are seen in EUVI A 304 appearing from behind the limb, indicating the source that is far behind the limb, as seen from STEREO A. The much fainter shock can be best seen mostly as it pushes the streamer in the south south west towards the east. Likely deflection of about 10 to 20 degrees eastward relative to the source at W125 caused by a large coronal hole located to the northwest of Active Region 4012.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow jet/outflow seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO and in 2 timestamps surrounding a data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source was found on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor faint and narrow CME best seen to the east in SOHO LASCO C2 and in a couple of early timestamps of C3 and fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source was found on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: An extremely faint fuzzy CME/outflow/possible partial halo to the north-northwest, seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and even more faintly for a few early timestamps in C3, but not seen in STEREO A COR2, likely because of faintness. Better seen in running difference imagery. Its source is most likely the medium-size but pretty faint dimming seen starting ~2025-03-16T10:09Z, signifying eruption to the northwest of Active Region 4023 and centered (~N20W10), seen in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Partial halo CME with bulk seen to the north-northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and more towards the northeast in STEREO A COR2 imagery with faint, very wide shock developing in later frames with invisible leading edge containing lobes to the north and east in both SOHO and STEREO A imagery. The presumed source is an eruption from near the vicinity of Active Region 4032 (N35E35) seen as a dimming in SDO AIA 193 as early as 2025-03-16T18:04Z, disappearing loop structure in SDO AIA 171, and brightening in SDO AIA 304. There are two eruptions seen in GOES SUVI 304 imagery emanating from the same area, one seen at 18:49Z and another which appears more Earth-directed at 20:49Z. Triangulation using SOHO and STEREO A imagery seems to more strongly support Earth-directedness and deflection westward than the EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Very slow CME that looks like a slow streamer blowout, with a succession of almost identical faint fronts seen in both coronagraphs. The CME seems to accelerate, as seen in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery. There is no clear source seen on the disk, although there is a super minor dimming in AIA 193 centered around N30E10 starting after 00:30Z and continuing until 05Z, but it is extremely faint.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2. Also seen to the S in STEREO A COR2 but is not seen in SOHO LASCO C3. A possible source candidate is a very small eruption far to the SE (~S60E10) best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting about 2025-03-17T08:07Z; measurements align well with this possible source candidate.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME first seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-03-17T11:36Z. Also seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C3 but not visible in STEREO A COR2A imagery (where it would be near center disk from the perspective of STEREO A). The source of this CME is likely a small filament eruption centered around N12W30 which starts around 2025-03-17T10:36Z and is best seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen mostly in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 but with front not well seen in C3. The source of this CME is unclear. While there are some opening field lines visible on/beyond the east limb starting around 2025-03-17T10:54Z best seen in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 193, the fit with two coronagraphs indicates a lower longitude for the source.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Narrow pointy-nosed CME/outflow to the north, following preceding CMEs. No clear source has been found for it on disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright loop CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-17T19:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 17/18:23Z to 18/03:09Z. The source of this event is a double peaked C9.8 and M1.0 flare from AR AR 4033 (N25E40) peaking at 2025-03-17T19:19Z and 2025-03-17T19:33Z respectively. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 131, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption also seems to have a footpoint slightly further to the West at approx. N30E05, evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The field line loops appear to break off in stages, resulting in a second overlapping CME, CME: 2025-03-17T20:12Z. Both CMEs appear to exhibit a strong Northern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright, narrow CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-17T20:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 17/18:23Z to 18/03:09Z. The source of this event is a double peaked C9.8 and M1.0 flare from AR 4033 (N25E40) peaking at 2025-03-17T19:19Z and 2025-03-17T19:33Z respectively. This flare is visible in SDO AIA 131, along with field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171 and GOES SUVI 284. This eruption also seems to have a footpoint slightly further to the West at approx. N30E05, evidenced by dimming seen in SDO AIA 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. The field line loops appear to break off in stages, resulting in an earlier overlapping CME, CME: 2025-03-17T19:48Z. Both CMEs appear to exhibit a strong Northern deflection.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint, outflow-like CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-18T03:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this event is continued dimming and field line movement following the C9.8 and M1.0 double peaked flare at 2025-03-17T19:04Z and 2025-03-17T19:25Z respectively.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, outflow-like CME first seen in the North by SOHO LASCO C2 at 2025-03-18T06:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The likely source of this event is continued dimming and field line movement following the C9.8 and M1.1 double peaked flare at 2025-03-17T19:04Z and 2025-03-17T19:25Z respectively.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-03-18T08:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen at approx. S30E65 in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171 and 193, along with post eruptive arcades seen in SDO AIA 94, 131 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery and is not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting at 2025-03-18T15:39Z. The source is likely related to an opening of field lines visible beyond the northeast limb starting around 2025-03-18T15:30Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: This CME is faintly visible to the E/NE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. It is not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 data due to a data gap from 2025-03-18T15:39Z to 2025-03-19T03:09Z. The source appears to be a filament eruption beyond the E/NE limb starting around 2025-03-19T00:30Z as seen in SDO/AIA 131, 171, 193, and 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Bright streamer blowout CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The CME is visibly wider in STEREO A COR2 imagery than in SOHO imagery. The source of this CME appears to be a complex series of eruptions beginning with an eruption near N05E05 starting around 2025-03-19T00:39Z. This eruption may have triggered additional instability of nearby magnetic field line foot points, which may be associated with the streamer itself. Dimming is clearly seen to the east of the initial eruption location starting around 2025-03-19T06:00Z. It is also around this time that the CME appears to begin to speed up in the SOHO field of view with a more clear/defined front appearing around this time as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and wide loop CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Source is a filament eruption on or just beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery, likely placing it at a longitude between W120 to W130, and spanning from approximately N10 to N40, with liftoff of filamentary material seen starting at 2025-03-19T03:45Z. Simultaneous opening field line movement can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery, centered at N50, just to the north of the filament eruption, and possibly located further beyond the limb than the filament due to the faintness of this signature. A second, smaller loop of material centered at about N40 can be seen lifting off at 2025-03-19T06:15Z in STEREO A EUVI 304 which may be the source of the additional outflow seen in coronagraph imagery following this CME. Field line movement can also be seen on or beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 195. The quality and cadence of STEREO A COR2 imagery was affected during time of analysis due to a campaign scheduled to last from 2025-03-18 to 2025-03-24.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint but fast CME with an asymmetrical front, with a protruding nose to the south, seen directed to the west in SOHO with the start covered by the nighttime data gap in SOHO. Its source is the filament eruption seen on/behind the SW limb: as ejecta/prominence in AIA 304 (there are actually two ejectas - a more southern complex shaped loop-like prominence seen at 2025-03-19T22:50Z at latitude of -21, and a fan-shaped ejecta to the north of it seen at latitude of -7 at 2025-03-19T223:46Z. This eruption is also seen as fast opening of field lines behind the limb in AIA 193/171 starting at 2025-03-19T222:01Z and later (starting at 2025-03-19T223:21Z) as bright post-eruptive arcades on/behind the limb in AIA 131. There is an associated long duration occulted C6.0 flare peaking at 2025-03-20T00:07Z from behind the limb (bright arcades). It is possible that the flare is from former Active Region 4018 (S21W100).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint loop CME visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, with a faint flux rope feature more visible in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is the ejection of material from just beyond the southwest limb, first distinctly seen as a distinct instance of opening field lines and ejecta starting around 2025-03-19T23:15Z in GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery. Post-eruptive brightening extends onto the disk spanning from about S10 to S15 and W80 to W90, as seen in SDO AIA 304 at 2025-03-19T23:40Z. Associated surrounding field line movement extends into the northern hemisphere on or beyond the western limb, and some northern deflection occurs as the material erupts.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Loop CME with brighter, narrower bulk and fainter shock visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 during a STEREO A COR2 data gap. The source of the CME appears to the ejection of material from near the vicinity of Active Region 4022 just near N08W75, first distinctly seen as a distinct instance of opening field lines and brightening starting around 2025-03-20T17:24Z in SDO AIA 193 and 304 imagery. Faint flickering field lines far off the western limb seen in GOES SUVI 284 suggest that a component of this large scale eruption may be far-sided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. This CME is slow to evolve and appear as a defined front in the LASCO C2 field-of-view, and appears more clear in LASCO C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source for this CME is not observed as a distinct source, but appears to be continued outflow from CME 2025-03-20T17:12Z from AR 14022 centered at N08W75, corroborated via triangulation in the STEREO_CAT tool.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and to the S in two available frames of STEREO COR2A before a data gap begins at 2025-03-21T15:09Z. No source for this CME is observed in SDO and GOES imagery, suggesting a far-sided source alongside comparison between the CME direction in white light SOHO LASCO and STEREO COR2A imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint halo CME with a bulk visible mainly to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery (more easily seen in difference imagery). There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event due to a data gap. The source of this CME appears to be a large dimming region centered near N02E07 starting around 2025-03-21T15:49Z with a southeast directionality based on the minor EUV wave visible in SDO/AIA 211 and 193 imagery. There's a large coronal hole situated E/SE of the dimming region and a separate coronal hole due west of the dimming region which may have contributed to the deflection visible on the solar disk in SDO/AIA imagery. This source location appears to be a sympathetic eruption to the M1.2 flare from AR14028 (S17W33) seen to the SW in SDO/AIA 131 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. No STEREO A COR2 imagery for this event due to a data gap. The source of this CME may be the M1.2 flare from AR14028 (S17W33) as seen in SDO/AIA 131 and 193. There is clear dimming and moving/opening field lines visible to the SW of the eruption suggesting deflection. This may be due to a coronal hole due north of the source location.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME seen to the north-north-east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the north in STEREO A COR2 (along the northern streamer). Its source is the filament eruption seen beyond the north-north-east limb starting ~2025-03-22T07:18Z in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 304/284, with coronal signatures including a large prominence/ejecta (or even double ejecta) in AIA 171, SIVI 304/284 and as faint opening of field lines in AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption near Active Region 14037 (N22W32) starting around 2025-03-22T13:20Z seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

N20E70) beginning at approx. 26/13:28Z as seen in GOES SUVI 171 and 195.

note: A very faint loop-like CME to the southeast. There is a series of consecutive faint fronts, one of which is a bit brighter than the others and has been analyzed as the main front, but this brighter front is preceded by more faint fronts. The source of this CME is possibly the M1.5 flare from AR 14048 (S15E80) peaking at 2025-03-30T01:48Z. This CME is preceded by a narrow jet seen at 2025-03-29T23:12Z. It is possible that the jet is associated with the M1.9 flare, while this CME is associated with the M1.5 flare, both from AR 14048. The exact association with flares is not certain. Coronal signatures associated with the flares are relatively minor but very clear: an opening of field lines on/close to the SE limb seen in SDO AIA 193/171 and GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-03-29T23:13Z, followed by post-eruptive arcades seen on the limb in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284. There is also minor ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-03-29T23:07Z.

note: Faint CME seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, and directly S in STEREO COR2A. The source is likely dimming in the far southern area of the disk, centered around S60W20, observed in SDO AIA 193 around 2025-04-04T15:00Z. This may, unlikely, be related to a C4.4 flare from AR 14502 (S23W29) which peaked at 2025-04-04T14:46Z, it is difficult to discern if this flare erupted in this deflected direction, the dimming at S60W20 is an sympathetic eruption, or if the dimming at S60W20 is entirely separate. Thus it is not currently attributed as a source, and noted for completion of the analysis.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the N in STEREO A COR2. Source is a filament eruption from just beyond the NW limb. A prominence from just beyond the limb can be seen beginning to liftoff starting at 2025-04-04T16:08Z in GOES SUVI 304. Opening field lines seen in GOES SUVI 284 and ejecta seen in GOES SUVI 304 both show strong northern deflection of this eruption, with ejecta traveling nearly due north. STEREO A EUVI 195 and 304 show that the prominence was centered at about N30 and spanned from W82-W92 (in SDO coordinates).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint outflow-like CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Source is narrow ejecta and brightening seen at N20W97 (SDO AIA coordinates) in STEREO A EUVI 304 at 2025-04-04T17:45Z. This small eruption may have possibly disrupted surrounding coronal material, resulting in the faint, wide, and slow leading edge which surrounds the narrow flux rope visible in SOHO LASCO C2. This CME overlaps to the south of the preceding CME:2025-04-04T16:36Z. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-04T17:38Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. No clear source of this CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A bright symmetrical partial halo seen to the east in both coronagraphs. Its source is a clear, wide opening of field lines behind the east limb seen ~2025-04-05T03:55Z in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284, later followed by post-eruptive arcades gradually appearing from behind the east limb, as seen in SDO AIA 193/304/131. It overlaps with a slightly later CME that is seen as a more full halo in STEREO A.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A partial halo CME to the northeast, significantly overlapping with the 2025-04-05T04:00Z CME, and more clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 imagery, in which its front is seen as a separate northeastern halo-like front, following the more eastern front of the earlier 2025-04-05T04:00Z CME. In SOHO its front is harder to trace because of the overlap of two CMEs. Its source is likely far behind the east limb and might be indicated by the large filament behind the northeast limb moving northward, as seen in AIA SDO 304 and GOES SUVI 304 and 284 imagery after 2025-04-05T05:00Z, although this filament is more likely to be the source of a later, more northern, 2025-04-05T09:48Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint northward CME with messy multiple fronts, overlapping with 2025-04-05T04:00Z and 2025-04-05T06:36Z CMEs (this overlap makes analysis difficult). The start of the CME is likely significantly earlier, around 2025-04-05T08:36Z, but its front in the early timestamps is very difficult to discern because of the overlap. The source could be the large filament behind the northeast limb moving northward, as seen in SDO AIA 304 and GOES SUVI 304 after 2025-04-05T05:00Z, but it is unclear whether this filament is the source of this CME - or the 2025-04-05T06:36Z CME.
