note: CME first visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-18T19:36Z. Also visible to the SE in STEREO A COR2 but is obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. A possible source candidate is an eruption on or near the SE limb starting around 2025-04-18T18:48Z in SDO AIA 304. There is also some field line movement over the SE limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting around the same time. Based on a triangulated measurement using SWPC_CAT, there would need to be a considerable amount of deflection for this candidate to be the source.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-19T00:00Z. Also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3 but is partially obscured by the pylon. The start of the CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap starting from 2025-04-18T22:38Z to 2025-04-19T02:38Z, and following the data gap the leading edge is out of the field of view. This CME is associated with an M4.4 flare peaking at 2025-04-18T23:50Z and ejecta from on/beyond the SE limb (~S29E90). A Type II radio burst was also observed. The flare and associated ejecta are seen across SDO AIA and GOES SUVI wavelengths but are most clearly seen in SDO AIA 304 and SDO AIA 131. A wider, possible shock front is visible in a few early frames of SOHO LASCO C2, but quickly fades away and was determined to not be measurable. The CME experiences continued southward deflection through propagation.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME faintly visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The CME is partially obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. The source is likely farsided, and opening field lines can be best seen beyond the SE limb starting at 2025-04-19T06:14Z in SDO AIA 193 and in SDO AIA 171 in ISWA. The eruption is not clearly visible in STEREO A EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and very narrow CME to the east in SOHO LASCO C2, a few frames of SOHO LASCO C3 before it's too faint to track, and three frames of STEREO A COR2 imagery before a data gap. There is no clear identifiable source for this CME.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Semi-faint CME to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 (also visible in GOES-19/CCOR-1). The source is field line movement seen to the south beyond the limb in SDO/AIA 171 and 193 as well as in GOES SUVI 335 starting around 2025-04-19T16:48Z. This is likely a far-sided event. There is no STEREO A imagery for this event due to a data gap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible in running difference imagery to the S about half way into the FOV of SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-19T19:36Z. Also seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C3. CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. The CME could be continued outflow following CME: 2025-04-19T17:00Z. A possible source is some faint field line movement to the S starting around 2025-04-19T18:30Z best seen in SDO AIA 171 and SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-20T09:24Z. Also seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME overtakes a slower loop originating from close to the same source with a start time of 2025-04-20T08:48Z. The source of this CME is likely a rising loop of plasma seen on/near the SE limb for a few hours prior to the CME start time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no signatures on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the southeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided and may be related to faint field line movement visible over the southeast limb starting around 2025-04-20T18:00Z as seen in GOES SUVI 171 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the northwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery but is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is a filament eruption on/near the northwest limb (centered near N35W80) starting around 2025-04-20T21:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines is visible over the northwest limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first visible to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-21T08:12Z. Also seen to the SE for a few frames in STEREO A COR2 but is likely obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. This CME is much easier to see in running difference imagery. There is no definitive source for this CME, but there is some general movement from the vicinity of AR 14068 best seen in SDO AIA 193 for a couple hours prior to the CME start time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-21T10:12Z. Also visible to the W in SOHO LASCO C3 and for a few frames in STEREO A COR2. The source of this CME is most likely an eruption near the WNW limb starting around 2025-04-21T08:45Z. It is seen across all SDO AIA wavelengths; however, it is best seen as some brightening and field line movement on the WNW limb in SDO AIA 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO COR2A. The source of this CME is most likely some plasma seen leaving the disk off the WNW limb, best seen in SDO AIA 193 and SDI AIA 171 starting around 2025-04-21T12:43Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Two heavily overlapping flux rope CMEs from the same source seen to the south in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Source is two instances of significant dimming and opening field lines seen from the same location, AR 4065 (S31E10), starting at 2025-04-22T06:37Z then at 2025-04-22T07:24Z. There appears to be southern deflection in the UV imagery. Post eruptive brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 193 starting at 2025-04-22T08:13Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source of this CME is a filament eruption stretching from N18E70 to N30E50, centered around N25E65. The eruption is seen starting around 2025-04-22T09:12Z in SDO/AIA 304 with moving/opening field lines visible in SDO/AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the west in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. It has a bright core that fills more to the right side of the CME with a more faint leading edge. The source is an eruption from AR 14060 (N08W90) on/just beyond the western limb associated with an M1.3 flare, filament ejecta, and post-eruptive arcades as best seen in GOES SUVI 131, 304, and 171. This source is also visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 and SDO/AIA imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet CME seen to the west-northwest in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs, potentially associated with an eruption beyond the western limb as seen by moving field lines in SDO AIA 171 off the northwest limb around 2025-04-22T15:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, puff-like loop CME seen to the north in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the northwest and widening with time as the CME propagates, the CME is with high confidence likely originating from the far-side as suggested by this geometry and there are no sources on the Earth-facing disk to suggest this CME originates from the Earth-facing solar disk.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Inner loop CME in a set of concentric loop CMEs first seen at 2025-04-22T20:36Z in SOHO LASCO C2 to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the northwest in STEREO A COR2. The source likely originates from the far-sided as suggested by this geometry; there is broad field line movement seen developing over hours to the NE in SDO AIA 171 but no large-scale eruption seen.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Flux rope CME visible to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and in STEREO A COR2. Source is suspected to be a gradual streamer blowout, and there is some dimming visible in SDO AIA 193 starting at 2025-04-23T06:40Z from N20W45, which may be indicative of a footpoint of one of the rising loops of this streamer liftoff.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME visible to the SW in STEREO A COR2 imagery. No SOHO imagery available currently due to a data gap. The source appears to be beyond the SW limb starting around 2025-04-23T07:53Z in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO/AIA 171 as moving/opening field lines. The source is not clear in STEREO A EUV imagery.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-23T19:00Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap from 23/18:38Z to 24/02:38Z. The source of this event is a minor filament lift off seen along the NE limb beginning at approx. 23/17:27Z in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-24T00:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames, however a majority of this CME is blocked by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, but fits between SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2 suggest a far sided source. This CME does not have a very clearly defined front.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME first seen in the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-24T04:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is some minor brightening and field line movement seen along the East limb in SDO AIA 94 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Bright CME first seen in the NW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-24T06:36Z as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen along the NW limb (centered at approx. N30W90, footpoints located at approx. N40W50 and N25W100) in SDO AIA, STEREO A EUVI and GOES SUVI 304 with early liftoff beginning at approx. 24/05:24Z. Field line opening is also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, GOES SUVI 284, and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen in the southwest by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-24T08:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is likely far-sided, as indicated by field line opening seen behind the West limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 beginning at ~2025-04-24T07:54Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like CME first seen to the East by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-24T13:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is minor opening field lines seen along the East limb in SDO AIA 193 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the South in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2024-04-24T14:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. The source of this event is a Southern deflected eruption from AR 4065 (S31W22) beginning at approx. 24/13:34Z. This eruption and subsequent Southern dimming can be seen in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211. This deflection is likely due to the Active Region's proximity to a large positive polarity coronal hole.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Narrow CME visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is not found in EUV imagery, and the CME is likely farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A super narrow faint jet to the east in both coronagraphs, better seen in running difference imagery. There was no source for it found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Loop CME visible to the W in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and W in STEREO A COR2. Source is an eruption beyond the W limb, with opening field lines and ejecta located at about N00W123 as seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195, starting at 2025-04-26T07:05Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 and E in STEREO A COR2. Source is a small eruption seen from AR 14075 located at S11E45 starting at 2025-04-26T07:09Z. Brightening can be seen in SDO AIA 304, and narrowly opening field lines and a small amount of dimming can be seen in SDO AIA 193, 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint and narrow CME to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 and E in STEREO A COR2. Source is a small eruption from AR 14075 at S11E43 seen starting as early as 2025-04-26T09:57Z. Brightening and a small amount of ejecta can be seen in SDO AIA 304. Brightening and field line movement can be seen in SDO AIA 193, 171. Ejecta can be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 at timestamp 2025-04-26T10:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint CME visible to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. There is no STEREO A COR2 imagery available for this CME due to a data gap. The source of this CME is a filament eruption from the area of Active Region 14065 (S31W51) which is located in the middle of a large southern coronal hole. The filament eruption starts around 2025-04-26T19:00Z as seen in SDO/AIA 304, 193, 211, and 171 spanning the area of ~S30W45 to ~S40W55.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Narrow CME to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-27T15:36Z. CME is also visible to the N in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not seen in STEREO A COR2. The start time is somewhat ambiguous as the CME is very faint and less defined in SOHO LASCO C2. There is no good source candidate on the Earth-facing disk. However, a couple of possibilities are some minor movement along a filament centered about 15 degrees N of AR 14073 beginning around 2025-04-27T14:36Z and a minor puff of ejecta from approximately N40E30 beginning around 2025-04-27T15:16Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: CME first seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-27T17:00Z. CME is also visible to the E in SOHO LASCO C3 but is not visible in STEREO A COR2. The CME is visible in running difference imagery one frame earlier than in white light imagery. The source of this CME is most likely a small filament eruption from on/near the E limb starting around 2025-04-27T16:14Z as seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Very faint CME to the NE in SOHO, best seen in running difference imagery. It has a fuzzy front (except in a couple earliest timestamps of SOHO LASCO C2). The CME is extremely faint in C3 and even in C2 the front disappears after a few early timestamps. The CME is fully covered by a nighttime data gap in STEREO A. Its source is most likely an eruption best seen in GOES SUVI 284 from an unnumbered AR/plage region (~N20E40) to the NE of AR 14076 beginning at 2025-04-27T23:25Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 and to the south southeast in STEREO A COR2, with a clear flux rope seen in C2 running difference imagery. The source could be a minor eruption just west of AR 4068, centered ~(S25W20) at 2025-04-28T07:19Z seen in SDO AIA 304/193, on the boundary with the eastern part of the large SW coronal hole (so there could be an eastward deflection).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2. Also seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a slow movement of field lines and some material seen rising from on or beyond the NW limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-04-28T07:17Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME first seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-04-28T15:48Z. Also seen to the N in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME is best seen in running difference imagery and partially overlaps with earlier, slower CME: 2025-04-28T10:36Z. Later in propagation into SOHO LASCO C3, the CME appears to accelerate. This acceleration could be caused by an additional front that is sporadically visible for a few frames across SOHO LASCO C2/C3 but is not independently measurable. No additional coronal signatures were visible as possible sources for this CME; however, due to the far northern latitude (~N85), a very wide range of longitudes are possible. The source could be farsided.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: First of three of a series of minor visible outflows seen to the north and northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 occurring between 2025-04-28T23:00Z and 2025-04-29T03:24Z; may possibly be associated with a minor filament eruption occurring near N40W05 as seen in GOES SUVI 284 imagery and SDO AIA 304 seen around 2025-04-28T20:00Z, but probably far-sided as suggested by the continued appearance of similar-looking outflows despite no major source signature on the Earth-facing disk; some weakly moving field lines high off the northern limb between 2025-04-29T02:00Z and 04:00Z may suggest far-sidedness of at least one of these events. This event is not seen in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Second of three of a series of minor visible outflows seen to the north and northeast in SOHO LASCO C2 occurring between 2025-04-28T23:00Z and 2025-04-29T03:24Z; probably far-sided as suggested by the continued appearance of similar-looking outflows despite no major source signature on the Earth-facing disk; some weakly moving field lines high off the northern limb between 2025-04-29T02:00Z and 04:00Z may suggest far-sidedness of at least one of these events. This event is seen in STEREO A COR2 due to the northwest.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Third of three of a series of minor visible outflows seen to the north in SOHO LASCO C2 occurring between 2025-04-28T23:00Z and 2025-04-29T03:24Z; probably far-sided as suggested by the continued appearance of similar-looking outflows despite no major source signature on the Earth-facing disk; some weakly moving field lines high off the northern limb between 2025-04-29T02:00Z and 04:00Z may suggest far-sidedness of at least one of these events. This event is seen in STEREO A COR2 due to the northwest.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Jet-like, narrow CME with diffuse leading edge seen to the west in SOHO LASCO C2 and also to the west in STEREO A COR2; the source is not clear but may be potentially associated with an eruption occurring near or just beyond the western limb as seen in GOES SUVI 284 and SDO AIA 171 around 2025-04-29T07:00Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint, jet-like CME first seen in the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-19T13:24Z. This CME fades before exiting the FOV in C2, and is therefore not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 or STEREO A COR2. The source of this event is minor brightening and field line movement seen near AR 4079 (N09E75) exhibiting Northern deflection in SDO AIA 131 and 193.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Fast jet CME seen to the SW in STEREO A COR2 during a SOHO C2/C3 data gap likely in excess of 1000 km/s. The source at first glimpse and with higher confidence appears to be an eruption just beyond the western limb as seen mostly by quickly darkening field lines off the southwest limb in SDO AIA 171 around 2025-04-29T14:00Z, but with low confidence may be associated with Active Region 4070 (S12W51) as some minor darkening in the active region seen best in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-04-29T14:00Z. Measurement will be created assuming the limb-related source.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Jet-like CME first seen in the West by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-04-29T17:53Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. There is no clear source seen on the disk for this event, as triangulation suggests a far sided source.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-29T22:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-29T19:23Z. The source of this event is slow rising and opening field lines seen along the NE limb in SDO AIA 171, 193 and 211.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-04-29T23:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which began at 2025-04-29T19:23Z. The source of this event is a C7.3 flare from AR 4065 (S31W91) and subsequent filament eruption as seen exhibiting Southern deflection in SDO AIA 131, 304 and GOES SUVI 304. Wide opening field lines are also visible in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow, fast CME to the SW in STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. There is currently a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2 and C3 imagery. The source is seen as moving/opening field lines starting around 2025-05-01T08:39Z to the SW in SDO/AIA 193 and 171. An associated small filament eruption is also visible in SDO/AIA 304 and STEREO A EUVI 304 to the SW. This eruption is likely associated with old AR 14065 which rotated off the Earth-facing disk late on 2025-04-29. The estimated longitudes of the source are (~S31W110 to ~S31W125) based on calculation of average rotation and visible inspection of STEREO A EUV imagery. This active region is situated within a coronal hole which may attribute to deflection.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint narrow CME with a peculiar slanted front seen to the east in both coronagraphs. No clear source for it was found in EUV imagery, although there is continuous minor movement of field lines beyond the east limb seen in SDO AIA 171.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: A faint CME seen to the east in both coronagraphs (but only seen very faintly in a couple early timestamps of SOHO LASCO C3). No clear coronal signatures for this CME were found in EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Faint, narrow CME seen to the southeast in SOHO C2, STEREO A COR2, and faintly in GOES CCOR-1, all generally disappearing before leaving their respectively field of views. The source appears to be a minor filament eruption occurring near S30W65 seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304, and GOES SUVI 284 as various brightenings around 2025-05-02T09:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen in the NE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-05-03T11:53Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR in later frames. The source of this event is an eruption seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211 beginning at approximately 2025-05-03T10:39Z centered at approximately N10E55, but exhibiting some Eastern deflection. Dimming can be seen in SDO AIA 211 and post eruptive arcades are visible in SDO AIA 131 and 193.

These filaments are best seen in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304, along with dimming and field line opening seen in SDO AIA 171, 193, 211 and GOES SUVI 284. note: A relatively bright CME seen to the east in all three coronagraphs. Coronal signatures include intense dimming, brightening, post-eruptive arcades and even a wide EUV wave seen almost reaching the central meridian in SDO AIA.

note: Wide CME observed to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source is a broad opening of field lines to the northeast centered on disk around N15E61, north of AR 14100 (N08E61), observed best in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 284 beginning slowly around 2025-05-27T07:16Z and faster starting around 2025-05-27T08:06Z. Accompanied by some slight dimming in SDO AIA 193 well north of this central point, spanning a thin arc ~N35E90 to ~N35E40, then down to ~N08E33. This minor increase in brightening is associated with a brief post-eruptive arcade seen from Active Region 14100 and is accompanied by a long-duration post-eruptive brightening from the surrounding area near and around Active Region 14100. Long-duration post-eruptive brightening near and around Active Region 14100 can be seen in SDO AIA 131. Two brief brighter arcades forming at Active Region 14100 resulted in a C4.5 and a C5.0 flare.

The same eruption is visible in STEREO A EUVI imagery just to the SW of center disk. This would explain why the CME is not visible in COR2A (it is mostly nose on from the perspective of STEREO A and quite narrow).

The source of this CME appears to be continued dimming and field line movement following a wide eruption associated with an M3.4 class flare from AR 4100. These features can be seen clearly in SDO AIA 211. This CME overlaps with earlier CME: 2025-05-30T06:38Z which is associated with the M3.4 flare, where as this event is more associated with the subsequent dimming following the flare.

note: Full-halo CME first seen in GOES-19 CCOR-1. Also seen in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 after the beginning of a downlink period with data streaming in starting at about 2025-05-31T01:00Z. No STEREO A COR2 imagery was available in real time for this CME due to a data gap which began at 2025-05-30T19:09Z. The source is an M8.1 flare from AR 14100 (N12E12). A significant area of opening field lines and dimming can be seen from near AR 14100 (N12E12) in SDO AIA 193/171/131/304 and GOES SUVI 284/304 beginning at 2025-05-30T23:47Z, immediately after the flare. Dimming and field line movement extends along a nearby filament which spans across most of the Earth-facing disk, stretching from approximately N30E05 to S15W35, snaking through the entire NW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk in a shape resembling the number '3'. It appears that most of the filamentary material ejected is from the upper lobe of the '3', and departs from approximately N10W15.

The source of this event may be related to a minor eruption from AR 14104 (N06E41), exhibiting Eastern deflection. This eruption can be seen in SDO AIA and STEREO A EUVI 304, along with brightening seen in SDO AIA 94, 131 and field line movement in SDO AIA 171 and 193.

There are two lobes of this CME, each corresponding to a piece of filament that erupted. Both pieces of filamentary material can be seen erupting simultaneously in GOES SUVI 304 imagery, so both lobes are therefore considered as one CME. The filament is located at latitude N40 and spanned from approximately W90 to W130. Gradual liftoff is seen starting as early as 2025-07-05T06:23Z in GOES SUVI 304. note: A faint CME with a fuzzy front dissipating soon (or father a sequence of fuzzy faint fronts following each other almost immediately). Its initial front is too faint to be seen in C3, but it can faintly be seen as one of the follow-up fronts in C3. The source of this CME is a filament eruption happening behind the northwest limb as seen from STEREO A EUVI 195/304 - especially note the wide opening of field lines/restructuring of magnetic field on/behind the limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 starting at 2025-07-06T17:05Z, and a bit later a minor but bright post-eruptive peeking from behind the west limb in EUVI A 304. SDO AIA 304/171 and GOES SUVI 304 also possibly see this eruption - but as a loop-like filament that seems to slowly depart the limb around 17:18Z, after first starting to rise as a sizable loop some time as early as 15:30Z.

This CME front appears to be triggered alongside simultaneous fronts in other directions from this same eruption, observed as CME 2025-07-08T04:24Z (bright NE bulk) and CME 2025-07-08T04:48Z (far north).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME observed to the far north in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, blocked by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The source is likely sympathetic with an eruption on or just beyond the NE limb around N22 that had an M2.4 flare visible in SDO AIA 171 which began at 2025-07-08T03:42Z, also observed well in SDO AIA 171/193 and GOES SUVI 171/195/284 as wide field line opening, an EUV wave, and a brief post eruptive arcade. This front is not from the main ejecta of this eruption, but appears to be triggered alongside simultaneous fronts in other directions, observed as CME 2025-07-08T04:24Z (bright NE bulk) and CME 2025-07-08T04:36Z (NE, more in ecliptic).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: This CME is visible to the west in STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event is not observed in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 or GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source is likely far-sided, and may be related to an opening of field lines on or beyond the western limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 imagery starting around 2025-07-09T10:55Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is very faint but visible to the south in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery and to the southwest in STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is unknown and likely far-sided, but may be related to an eruption visible on or slightly beyond the southwest limb near latitude S50 as seen in STEREO A EUVI imagery starting around 2025-07-09T11:15Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and to the northwest in STEREO A COR2 imagery. This event is blocked by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk that align with the direction of this event.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: The CME start time is actually 2025-07-09T13:25Z (4 hours earlier than the start time in DONKI). This is because SOHO LASCO was not available on the day when the CME was analyzed and entered into DONKI. CME with a flux rope clearly seen in coronagraphs, first seen to the NW in GOES CCOR-1 starting around 2025-07-09T17:30Z. CME is also seen to the N in STEREO A COR2. CME was originally covered by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, but LASCO eventually backfilled. A possible source for this CME is a filament eruption starting to the SW of AR 14137 beginning around 2025-07-09T15:30Z and moving eastward - faint ejecta can be seen leaving the disk in SDO AIA 304. If this candidate is the source of the CME, there is some significant deflection to the NW.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: Minor faint CME with two lobes seen to the north in SOHO LASCO and in GOES CCOR-1 and to the north in STEREO A COR2 and closely following the wider, slightly slower, preceding CME: 2025-07-09T17:30Z. This CME is partially obscured by the pylon in C3. Its source has not been found, but is likely the same Active Region 4137 that produced the preceding, 2025-07-09T17:30Z CME.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Narrow CME first seen to the E in GOES CCOR-1 starting around 2025-07-09T21:20Z. CME is not seen in STEREO A COR2 and is covered by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. There is not a good source candidate on the Earth-facing disk, so the source is possibly far-sided.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME observed to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and SW in STEREO A COR2. No source is observed in SDO, GOES, or STEREO A imagery, which combined with the triangulation of coronagraph imagery concludes that this source is far-sided.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and to the SW in STEREO A COR2. Source is a filament eruption from beyond the SE limb from the perspective of SDO AIA and GOES SUVI and beyond the SW limb from the perspective of STEREO A EUVI. Diffuse ejecta from beyond the SE limb can be seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting as early as 2025-07-11T09:52Z. In STEREO A EUVI 304, there may possibly be a rising loop from beyond the SW limb seen between the frames with timestamps 2025-07-11T07:45Z-08:15Z, followed by wider opening field lines between the frames with timestamps 2025-07-11T08:15Z-08:45Z. The first available frame of SOHO LASCO C2 in which the leading edge is well defined is the frame at timestamp 2025-07-11T10:24Z after a brief gap caused by a scheduled calibration of SOHO LASCO.
instruments: GOES: CCOR-1, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3

note: Faint CME to the NW seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and obscured by pylon in C3; not really seen in other coronagraphs. It is the second faint front (the earlier, 03Z front is even fainter and disappears really quickly in C2 imagery). Source is likely a slowly developing, messy eruption near AR 4037, centered ~(N32W23), starting as early as 2025-07-1tT00:54Z and lasting through the whole morning (at least to 5Z). The eruption location seems to move further west with time. Coronal signatures include developing faint dimming and faint post-eruptive arcades, as seen in SDO AIA 193/304, GOES SUVI 284 and STEREO A EUVI 195.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: A relatively narrow CME with a messy front visible to SSW in white light (as well as in running difference) imagery in all three coronagraphs. Seen more to the south and more faintly in STEREO A COR2. Its likely source is a filament seen erupting starting at 2025-07-12T08:45Z near the SW limb, as seen in SDO AIA imagery, centered very approximately at (S35W60). The source is seen in more detail in STEREO A EUV 304/195 imagery than in other EUV imagers: in STEREO EUVI 195 two simultaneous eruptions cam be seen - one in the AR 4134 (~S23W90), and the other in the filament located SE of this AR (~S35W45).
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME with fuzzy front seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 imagery (too fuzzy and faint to be traced in C3 and GOES CCOR-1), and so far covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. It disappears from C2 imagery after several timestamps because of it's faintness. Its source could be an eruption in former Active Region 14134 (S21W95) that is now behind the west limb. The eruption is seen after 2025-07-12T15:30Z as an opening of field lines behind the limb in SDO AIA 193, GOES SUVI 284 and as bright post eruptive arcade seen on/behind the limb in SUVI 304. Eruption also likely seen on disk in STEREO A EUV imagery before the data gap in STEREO A, best seen as a brightening in Active Region 14134 starting around 2025-07-12T15:30Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: Fast CME seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR1 but so far covered by the gap in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph. Its source could be an eruption in the NE quadrant, with medium size dimming seen in AIA 193 starting after 2025-07-12T12:00Z and centered around (N20E52). There is also activity in AR 4136 (N19E32) at the time.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint CME with a narrower bulk and a wider, fainter possible shock front visible to the NNW in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 and to the N in STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. No source has been found for this CME in available EUV imagery.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Very narrow jet-like CME (less than 10 degree half-width) first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T16:12Z. CME is only visible in SOHO LASCO C2 and is much easier to see in running difference imagery. CME fades before leaving FOV of SOHO LASCO C2. The source is likely a small eruption from on/beyond the NE limb around 2025-07-13T14:42Z best seen in SDO AIA 304.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2

note: CME first seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T18:36Z. CME is also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1, and very faintly in STEREO A COR2. A possible source of this CME is a small eruption best seen near the SW limb in SDO AIA 304 beginning around 2025-07-13T18:03Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T19:24Z. CME is also seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is most likely some opening field lines from beyond the NW limb best seen in GOES SUVI 284 beginning around 2025-07-13T18:16Z. CME likely combines with following, faster CME: 2025-07-13T22:12Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen to the WNW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-07-13T22:12Z. CME is also seen to the WNW in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source is most likely an eruption from AR 14137 beginning around 2025-07-13T21:44Z best seen in GOES SUVI 284. The eruption can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 195 and STEREO A EUVI 304 beginning around 2025-07-13T18:35Z followed by an EUV wave. CME collides and likely combines with previous, slower CME: 2025-07-13T19:24Z.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Source is uncertain; there is no clear source in available UV imagery of the disk. Leading edge is not visible in STEREO A COR2. Source is uncertain, but may be subtle field line movement seen on or beyond the SE limb GOES SUVI 284.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1

note: Faint flux rope CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Exact source is uncertain, but is very likely associated with continued outflow to the NW from near AR 4137 (N19W81) or beyond the NW limb, following the eruptions associated with CME:2025-07-13T19:24Z and CME:2025-07-13T22:12Z which were both to the NW as well.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2

note: CME seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source is an eruption from former Active Region 14134 (S22W118) at 2025-07-14T13:45Z seen in STEREO A EUVI 304. This eruption immediately triggers the eruption of a nearby filament which spans from about S45W72 to S20W102 with liftoff starting at about 2025-07-14T15:15Z as seen in STEREO A EUVI 304. Opening field lines and ejecta can be seen on the SW limb, originating from AR 14134, and filamentary ejecta can be seen departing from the SW limb with heavy southward deflection as seen in GOES SUVI 304/284 and SDO AIA 304/193/171/131.
instruments: SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, GOES: CCOR-1

note: CME first seen to the South by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-07-14T19:38Z, as well as by GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a large amount of prominence material leaving the sun, following an earlier eruption from AR 14134 and resulting CME: 2025-07-14T14:36Z. Prominence material is seen beginning to leave the sun with this earlier eruption beginning at approx. 2025-07-14T15:15Z. This material then slowly stretches Southward along the Western limb and out of the field of view in SDO AIA and GOES SUVI 304 before finally fully disconnecting from the sun at approx. 2025-07-14T20:36Z.
instruments: STEREO A: SECCHI/COR2, SOHO: LASCO/C2, SOHO: LASCO/C3, GOES: CCOR-1
